</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,539]" pageId="10" pageNumber="433">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[323,450,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 31–35" captionStartId="10.[151,264,985,1010]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,557,959]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,553,965]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 31–35. Indomicrus chera gen. &amp; sp. n. Abdominal sternites III–VII in ventral view (31); aedeagus in ventral (32, 34) and lateral (33, 35) views. Arrows showing rows of foveate punctures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602460" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602460/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="433">Figs 32–35</figureCitation>
) elongate; AeL 
<quantity box="[625,727,153,179]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="10" pageNumber="433" unit="mm" value="0.33">0.33 mm</quantity>
; median lobe in ventral view drop-shaped, broadest in sub-basal third, in subapical area abruptly narrowing toward subtriangular, pointed apex of dorsal wall of aedeagus, ventrally ostium closed by rounded apical plate not reaching apex of ventral wall; endophallus with elongate median sclerotized structure with broad base, surrounded by group of elongate sclerites directed distad, and with arcuate and darkly sclerotized component transverse in relation to the long axis of aedeagus; each paramere with one apical and two tiny subapical setae.
</paragraph>
